snippet: Federal and state officials said that while they knew there was pent-up demand for health coverage, the number of visits to their exchanges was greater than anticipated.
abstract: Millions of Americans visit online health insurance exchanges as enrollment opens, suggesting broad national appetite for affordable coverage, but many quickly encounter technological problems that prevent them from getting rates, comparing plans or signing up; it remains unclear whether array of problems stem more from unanticipated heavy traffic or flaws in design.

byline.original: By ABBY GOODNOUGH, ROBERT PEAR and RICHARD PÉREZ-PEÑA
byline.contributor: Reporting was contributed by Ian Lovett, Dan Frosch, Lizette Alvarez, Manny Fernandez, Anemona Hartocollis, Ariel Kaminer, Steven Yaccino, Jon Hurdle and Kitty Bennett.
